WEBVTT

00:08.580 --> 00:12.580
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.260 --> 00:33.580
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.200 --> 00:37.920
And here are your hosts.

00:41.840 --> 00:43.860
This is Daryl A. and David Carson.

00:44.260 --> 00:47.600
Chad Oliver has never really been able to devote himself fully to writing science fiction,

00:47.800 --> 00:49.420
though he's been publishing it for over 30 years.

00:49.740 --> 00:53.680
He's also a teacher, a professor of anthropology at the University of Texas at Austin.

00:54.140 --> 00:57.580
As is true with many science fiction authors, Oliver starred as a writer, resulted from

00:57.580 --> 00:59.320
his fascination with reading science fiction.

00:59.620 --> 01:03.560
As a teenager, he discovered Edgar Rice Burroughs and his lush Martian stories and tried to get

01:03.560 --> 01:05.200
his hands on everything Burroughs published.

01:05.800 --> 01:11.140
Because of the addiction to Burroughs, one time when I was in a newsstand I saw a copy

01:11.140 --> 01:14.480
of the big old fat amazing stories.

01:16.180 --> 01:24.040
And it had a cover story by Burroughs called Tiger Girl and also a story by Eando Bender.

01:24.220 --> 01:30.080
You remember him or rather you remember them, Earl and Otto, called Adam Link saves the

01:30.080 --> 01:30.240
world.

01:30.240 --> 01:35.220
Anyway, I bought the copy of Amazing because I wanted to read the Burroughs story and I

01:35.220 --> 01:37.520
figured well I might as well read all this other stuff too.

01:38.040 --> 01:45.080
And there was a story in there by Edmund Hamilton called Treasure on Thunder Moon which I read

01:45.080 --> 01:47.180
and was immediately hooked.

01:47.320 --> 01:51.360
I thought this was the greatest thing I had ever read, maybe the greatest thing anybody

01:51.360 --> 01:52.140
had ever written.

01:52.900 --> 01:57.320
And I decided well by golly the thing to be is to be a professional writer and to write

01:57.320 --> 01:58.100
science fiction.

01:58.100 --> 02:08.880
And I got a second hand portable typewriter and I taught myself to type and I wrote something

02:09.880 --> 02:15.440
every week between the time I was 14 and when I was 21 when I sold my first story.

02:15.980 --> 02:17.940
And sent it all off.

02:18.360 --> 02:21.220
Editors were just immensely helpful.

02:21.620 --> 02:24.060
I never got form rejection slips.

02:24.860 --> 02:29.440
Even at 14 years old you can imagine the kind of junk you were writing at 14.

02:30.360 --> 02:34.860
But people like Sam Merlin for example would write me a little note, you know, we can't

02:34.860 --> 02:36.800
use this but keep trying and so forth.

02:37.760 --> 02:45.280
And in effect what really happened was that I got hooked on science fiction and I just

02:45.280 --> 02:47.600
thought science fiction writers must be gods.

02:48.060 --> 02:49.460
And I wanted to be one.

02:49.540 --> 02:51.860
I figured that's as close to a god as I could get.

02:53.100 --> 02:58.020
So I went at it and I kept writing until I sold my first story and I sold every one

02:58.020 --> 02:58.700
I've written since.

03:06.260 --> 03:10.280
But Oliver was also pursuing an academic career and he took a master's degree in English

03:10.280 --> 03:11.420
from the University of Texas.

03:11.740 --> 03:15.520
His master's thesis was written on magazine science fiction, the first academic thesis

03:15.520 --> 03:17.040
written on that particular subject.

03:17.340 --> 03:21.020
With a degree in English you might have expected Oliver to become an English teacher or a full

03:21.020 --> 03:22.240
time writer of science fiction.

03:22.660 --> 03:23.960
We asked him why he didn't become either.

03:25.080 --> 03:33.740
Actually I was briefly, after I got my MA I taught English at the University for one

03:33.740 --> 03:39.760
year and there were two troubles that were involved in that situation.

03:40.160 --> 03:42.700
From my point of view I don't know what troubles the students had.

03:43.880 --> 03:50.460
But the two troubles were basically that by the time I had started to teach English I

03:50.460 --> 03:54.740
was so much into anthropology that I already knew that that's what I wanted to do.

03:55.580 --> 03:59.820
And I really was just teaching the English because I had told Ransom I would.

04:01.580 --> 04:06.820
And the other aspect of it was there's nothing like teaching freshman English for a year

04:06.820 --> 04:10.060
to convince you that that's not what you want to do for the rest of your life.

04:11.000 --> 04:12.740
So that was the end of it.

04:12.940 --> 04:16.640
I left then went to UCLA to graduate school in anthropology.

04:18.020 --> 04:21.660
I know that doesn't answer the question about why I didn't become a full time professional

04:21.660 --> 04:22.100
writer.

04:23.040 --> 04:25.480
But I'm not sure I can answer that question.

04:25.780 --> 04:30.640
Tony Boucher once said to me, sooner or later you're going to have to choose.

04:31.540 --> 04:32.840
And I never did.

04:33.260 --> 04:39.100
And I suppose that one reason was that I was particularly at that time when I was, you

04:39.100 --> 04:41.060
know, a hundred years younger than I am now.

04:41.920 --> 04:45.200
I was just as interested in anthropology as I was in writing.

04:45.200 --> 04:47.360
And I really wanted to teach anthropology.

04:48.340 --> 04:51.980
And so I tried to do both that was within different success.

04:53.160 --> 04:55.440
More of Science Fiction author, Chad Oliver, next time.

