12:20.540 --> 12:25.300
Chad Oliver's 1976 Science Fiction novel, Giants in the Dust, illustrates his background in anthropology.

12:25.800 --> 12:28.640
The book is based on an idea of an earth that is stagnant and lethargic.

12:29.140 --> 12:30.420
Everything man wants, he has.

12:30.720 --> 12:33.020
There are no challenges and as a result, no happiness.

12:33.500 --> 12:36.940
A man named Varnum and some companions have their brains wiped clean of all memories,

12:37.280 --> 12:39.880
and they're sent to another planet, uninhabited but earth-like.

12:39.880 --> 12:43.820
The idea is to have mankind start fresh and see if he'll make the same mistakes

12:43.820 --> 12:45.800
or take some alternate evolutionary path.

12:46.160 --> 12:50.360
With that in mind, the humans are left on the planet with no technological aid whatsoever.

12:50.880 --> 12:56.120
Varnum himself is a throwback, a tough hunter who hasn't succumbed to the softness and lethargy of the rest of humanity.

12:56.480 --> 13:00.040
When the humans reach the point, we begin to domesticate animals and practice agriculture.

13:00.300 --> 13:01.160
Varnum's stopping them.

13:01.380 --> 13:02.220
We asked Oliver why.

13:02.620 --> 13:05.220
Wouldn't Varnum's action and effect prevent civilization from developing?

13:06.220 --> 13:11.800
Well actually, the funny thing about giants in the dust, there are lots of funny things about giants in the dust,

13:12.980 --> 13:19.280
including the fact that that's not my title, and I have the faintest idea of what giants in the dust means

13:19.740 --> 13:22.140
in the context of that particular novel.

13:22.320 --> 13:23.880
I called it go back, go back.

13:24.920 --> 13:29.920
But it's about a kind of anthropology that most people are not familiar with.

13:29.920 --> 13:36.700
You know, almost all the anthropology and science fiction comes out really of the old Franz Boas,

13:36.760 --> 13:39.920
Ruth Benedict, cultural relativism position.

13:41.020 --> 13:45.820
And there's a whole new school in anthropology, if you can call it a school,

13:46.300 --> 13:51.100
and not just in anthropology because it gets into sociobiology and all sorts of things,

13:52.360 --> 13:56.640
which states in effect, you know, that there's more to human beings at birth

13:56.640 --> 14:00.800
than just being the traditional tabula rasa that there's some things built in.

14:01.880 --> 14:06.280
And what I was trying to do in giants in the dust or what was going on there

14:06.280 --> 14:12.720
was really to take the old deal about, suppose you took 50 people, 25 male, 25 female,

14:12.820 --> 14:15.900
and you cast them away on the traditional desert island.

14:16.520 --> 14:21.380
What would happen to them if they could somehow survive from infancy and grow into adulthood?

14:22.380 --> 14:32.340
And one possibility that hasn't been considered is that we have a kind of culture building device within us

14:32.340 --> 14:38.640
and that we would recreate a good deal of culture much more quickly than is usually assumed.

14:39.260 --> 14:42.860
And I was playing around with that idea in giants in the dust.

14:43.120 --> 14:49.300
And the reason why Varnum stops these various inventions and things

14:49.300 --> 14:53.460
is because he wants to give it time to unfold to see what will happen.

14:54.080 --> 14:59.080
But you may recall Varnum's the only character in the book who retains any memory.

14:59.780 --> 15:07.260
And at the end of the book, he finally decides that ethically the only thing he can do is to tell him,

15:07.480 --> 15:12.840
tell the other people, tell what he remembers of the culture back on earth,

15:13.100 --> 15:15.780
and to give them a fairer shot at what's going on.

15:29.720 --> 15:31.160
Final occurrences

15:31.160 --> 15:39.520
No, I wasn't. I think you can construct an argument to the effect that people

15:39.520 --> 15:43.060
in other kinds of societies, particularly hunting and gathering societies

15:43.060 --> 15:50.460
societies have some things that we don't have. It's not all one sided. Civilization

15:50.460 --> 15:57.520
is not an unmixed blessing. And people who live in those banned type of societies, they

15:57.520 --> 16:04.180
tend to be freer from stress. They tend to have fewer emotional problems than people

16:04.180 --> 16:11.160
who live in societies such as our own. And so I don't think it's a completely insane

16:11.160 --> 16:15.880
argument to say, you know, maybe we'd all be better off if we were still hunters and

16:15.880 --> 16:22.880
gatherers. But no, it's not a position I would advocate because I don't think it's a, it's

16:22.880 --> 16:26.720
not a realistic proposition outside the world of fantasy.

