18:07.020 --> 18:11.320
Oliver raises an interesting question. A man colonized a space, will the human race

18:11.320 --> 18:15.740
split into two separate species, spacers and earthers? The story is entitled, meanwhile,

18:15.940 --> 18:20.500
back on the reservation, and it appeared in the 1981 edition of Analog Magazine. As the

18:20.500 --> 18:24.600
title suggests, Earth becomes sort of a reservation containing the backwash of human culture,

18:25.000 --> 18:28.640
while the other worlds colonized by humans become the progressive mainstream of mankind's

18:28.640 --> 18:32.760
culture. We asked Oliver if he thought such a situation could occur as we move that into

18:32.760 --> 18:39.380
space. I think it's possible. Really, the genesis of,

18:40.180 --> 18:47.600
meanwhile, back on the reservation with two-fold. And one would simply be the kind of reaction

18:47.600 --> 18:53.460
that builds up in you when everybody talks about, hey, you know, here's the glorious

18:53.460 --> 18:59.460
future coming onward to the stars, everybody. When you stop and realize everybody's not

18:59.460 --> 19:10.680
going, and in fact 99.99% of the human population will live and die on this planet, and you've

19:10.680 --> 19:17.340
got to wonder, well, what about them? Are they people too? And it's anthropological,

19:17.340 --> 19:23.780
I think, primarily in the sense of they're in the same boat that so-called primitive

19:23.780 --> 19:30.760
peoples are on this planet today, that the march of culture, for one of another term,

19:31.420 --> 19:38.040
has passed them by to some extent. And they're sort of islands that are left in the stream

19:38.040 --> 19:43.980
and left behind, and yet they have all the problems of living the face that anybody else

19:43.980 --> 19:49.560
does. And I was just trying to raise the question, well, all right, what about the people who

19:49.560 --> 19:54.680
stay behind? Do we just write them off? Are they ciphers, or aren't they just as important

19:54.680 --> 19:57.780
to somebody that goes off to Alpha Centaurus or someplace?

20:03.560 --> 20:07.400
Oliver's been publishing science fiction for over 30 years, and for a good part of that

20:07.400 --> 20:10.980
time he's lived in Austin, Texas, and taught anthropology at the University of Texas.

20:11.420 --> 20:15.140
Oliver goes on to talk about, meanwhile, back on the reservation and reveals some interesting

20:15.140 --> 20:19.100
information about his background as a science fiction writer, and also about science fiction

20:19.100 --> 20:19.800
writers in Texas.

20:20.600 --> 20:25.860
The other thing that was involved in that story was that I had not written any short fiction

20:25.860 --> 20:34.600
in a while, and I got mixed up with the Turkey City group in Austin, which has been a source

20:34.600 --> 20:43.080
of untold joy in my life. And a number of people who were involved in that group, Lisa Tuttle

20:43.080 --> 20:48.960
and Howard Waldrop and a number of others, had urged me to try to do something again,

20:49.400 --> 20:55.260
not wait so long between stories. And meanwhile, back on the reservations, actually the first

20:55.260 --> 21:04.540
story I ever wrote that I submitted to criticism from other writers, and I learned a lot from

21:04.540 --> 21:10.540
them, and it was a very rewarding experience. And I can't tell you what a thrill it is for

21:10.540 --> 21:17.360
me to be living in some place like Austin and to find a whole colony of professional

21:17.360 --> 21:22.140
science fiction writers there, and not just there, but the fact that they're so good.

21:22.760 --> 21:28.060
You know, for something like 20 years, I was all alone in Texas. The closest thing there

21:28.060 --> 21:32.760
was to a science fiction convention or gathering in the old days was when Walt Miller and I

21:32.760 --> 21:38.940
got together for a six pack of beer and Kyle. And this is a brand new experience for me,

21:38.940 --> 21:45.320
and it's comparable only to the situation I was in when I was in Los Angeles in graduate

21:45.320 --> 21:52.360
school. And Ray Bradbury and Chuck Beaumont and Bill Nolan and Dick Matheson and all of

21:52.360 --> 21:57.140
us would get together and talk about stories. But we never criticized each other's manuscripts

21:57.140 --> 22:03.440
in a more or less formal session like that. Instead, you know, somebody would write something

22:03.440 --> 22:06.720
and if there was somebody they liked, they'd take it, hey, look at this, you know, you think

22:06.720 --> 22:11.260
I can do anything with it. And then 20 years more or less by myself, really.

